Session 1: Importing Data, Data Wrangling, and Tidy Data

No data science without data!

Objectives of todays session

  1. Learn how to import raw data in R.

  2. Creat tidy dataset from raw data using tidyr.

  3. Use dplyr package for data transformation.

Plan

  1. Read excel file, show arguments how they work
  2. Read tab-delimited file, show arguments how they work
  3. Read comma-sep files, show arguments how they work
  4. For other types of files, json, xml look for function in R
  5. Exercise: Import a sample CSV file and an Excel file into R from directory
  6. Introduction to dplyr packages.
  7. Common data manipulation tasks: filtering, selecting, mutating, summarizing.
  8. Grouping data and performing operations on groups.
  9. Joining data from different sources.
  10. Handling missing data.
  11. Exercise: ask students to do some basic operations on sample dataset from prev exercise

R script

create a new script file (File > New File > R Script)

## Copy this code in the R script

# Assigning numbers to variables
a <- 5
b <- 3

# Addition
sum_result <- a + b

# Subtraction
diff_result <- a - b

# Print the results
print("Results of Basic Math Operations:")
## [1] "Results of Basic Math Operations:"
print(paste("Sum: ", sum_result))
## [1] "Sum:  8"
print(paste("Difference: ", diff_result))
## [1] "Difference:  2"

Data types

num_variable <- 42.5
class(num_variable)

char_variable = "Welcome to the DS club"
class(char_variable)
## [1] "character"
logic_variable = TRUE
class(logic_variable)
## [1] "logical"
num_variable == 42.5
## [1] TRUE
num_variable >= 50
## [1] FALSE
class(num_variable == 42.5)
## [1] "logical"

R Functions

3 Key Properties of an R function.

  • functions have a name and they are case sensetive

  • following the name they have a pair of ()

  • inside (), function take 0 or more arguments

Why did the function go to therapy? It had too many issues with its arguments!
summ_two_numbers <- function(a=3, b=6){
  return(a+b)
}

summ_two_numbers()
## [1] 9
summ_two_numbers(5, 19)
## [1] 24

R Objects

Objects Can Contain Multiple Data Types

How do we create a vector.

numeric_vector_1 <- c(1, 2, 3, 4, 5)

numeric_vector_2 <- 1:5

Accessing elements of a numeric vector

numeric_vector_1[3] # Access the third element of the vector
## [1] 3
numeric_vector_1[2:3] # Access the second to third element of the vector
## [1] 2 3
numeric_vector_1[c(2,5)] # Access the second and fifth element of the vector
## [1] 2 5

Read data

Need help looking at the many arguments of read.table you can use? Its easy.

Type this on the console: ?read.table

Dont know what your file looks like? No issue. We can check by reading the file line by line. This works even when the file size in GBs and we dont have a software to open the file on our operating system.

# Specify the path to your file
file_path1 <- "Datasets/file_1_to_read.txt"

# Read the first few lines
readLines(file_path1, n = 5)
## [1] "Geneid\tCounts" "497097\t0"      "100503874\t0"   "100038431\t0"  
## [5] "19888\t0"

Note: You can not create a R dataframe and perform data analysis by reading a file line by line.

df1 = read.table(file_path1, sep="\t", header = TRUE)

Split cells with tidyr package

Tidy data is a standard way of mapping the meaning of a dataset to its structure.

Whats a tidy data

Exercise 5

1. load tidyr package

# Complete the following code

library(_ _ _)

2. load dplyr package

# Write the line to load dplyr package
# Let's create sample dataframe and look at some tidyr functions to merge and split data

splicing_data <- data.frame(
  Event_ID = c('ENSG1_AB', 
               'ENSG2_CD', 
               'ENSG3_EF', 
               'ENSG4_GH',
               'ENSG5_IJ'),
  PSI_value_1 = as.character(c('0.', '0.', '0.', '0.', '1.')),
  PSI_value_2 = as.character(c(1,2,3,4,0)),
  Group = c("A", "B", "B", "A", "A"), 
  Peak = c('NA', 5, "NA", 9, 'NA')
)

splicing_data
##   Event_ID PSI_value_1 PSI_value_2 Group Peak
## 1 ENSG1_AB          0.           1     A   NA
## 2 ENSG2_CD          0.           2     B    5
## 3 ENSG3_EF          0.           3     B   NA
## 4 ENSG4_GH          0.           4     A    9
## 5 ENSG5_IJ          1.           0     A   NA
tidy_splicing_data <- tidyr::unite(splicing_data, PSI_value_1, PSI_value_2, col="PSI_value", sep="", remove=TRUE)

tidy_splicing_data
##   Event_ID PSI_value Group Peak
## 1 ENSG1_AB       0.1     A   NA
## 2 ENSG2_CD       0.2     B    5
## 3 ENSG3_EF       0.3     B   NA
## 4 ENSG4_GH       0.4     A    9
## 5 ENSG5_IJ       1.0     A   NA
# return new dataframe with new defined column
# also we can remove old columns or retain them
# you could play with "sep" and "col" arguments
# tidyr::separate same as tidyr::separate_wider_delim
tidyr::separate(tidy_splicing_data, Event_ID, sep="_", into=c('ID', 'Splicing event'), remove=TRUE)
##      ID Splicing event PSI_value Group Peak
## 1 ENSG1             AB       0.1     A   NA
## 2 ENSG2             CD       0.2     B    5
## 3 ENSG3             EF       0.3     B   NA
## 4 ENSG4             GH       0.4     A    9
## 5 ENSG5             IJ       1.0     A   NA

Reshape data

pivot_longer and pivot_wider
# First of all, let's create sample dataframe and then reshape it

table2 <- data.frame(
  country = c("A", "A", "B", "B", "C", "C"),
  year = c(1999, 2000, 1999, 2000, 1999, 2000),
  cases = c("0.7K", "2K", "37K", "80K", "212K", "213K"),
  pop = c("19M", "20M", "172M", "174M", "1T", "1T")
)

table2
##   country year cases  pop
## 1       A 1999  0.7K  19M
## 2       A 2000    2K  20M
## 3       B 1999   37K 172M
## 4       B 2000   80K 174M
## 5       C 1999  212K   1T
## 6       C 2000  213K   1T
# Let's reshape it
tidyr::pivot_longer(table2, cols = c("cases","pop"), names_to = "type", values_to = "count")
## # A tibble: 12  4
##    country  year type  count
##    <chr>   <dbl> <chr> <chr>
##  1 A        1999 cases 0.7K 
##  2 A        1999 pop   19M  
##  3 A        2000 cases 2K   
##  4 A        2000 pop   20M  
##  5 B        1999 cases 37K  
##  6 B        1999 pop   172M 
##  7 B        2000 cases 80K  
##  8 B        2000 pop   174M 
##  9 C        1999 cases 212K 
## 10 C        1999 pop   1T   
## 11 C        2000 cases 213K 
## 12 C        2000 pop   1T

Dplyr Package

dplyr Verb What it Does
filter Retrieve rows based on specified values.
select Retrieve columns based on specified names.
mutate Add new variables to the data frame.
arrange Change the order of the rows based on variables.
summarize Compute summary statistics for the data.

Lets look at how those work.

table2
##   country year cases  pop
## 1       A 1999  0.7K  19M
## 2       A 2000    2K  20M
## 3       B 1999   37K 172M
## 4       B 2000   80K 174M
## 5       C 1999  212K   1T
## 6       C 2000  213K   1T

In our table the cases is a character data type. To perform any mathematical operations or comparisons. We must mutate this into an appropriate double.

table3 <- mutate(table2, cases = as.double(sub("K", "", cases))*1000)

table3
##   country year  cases  pop
## 1       A 1999    700  19M
## 2       A 2000   2000  20M
## 3       B 1999  37000 172M
## 4       B 2000  80000 174M
## 5       C 1999 212000   1T
## 6       C 2000 213000   1T

Now we can use filter to look for countries that have more than 3000 cases in 1999.

filter(table3, cases > 3000 & year == 1999)
##   country year  cases  pop
## 1       B 1999  37000 172M
## 2       C 1999 212000   1T

Joining, Transforming and Summarizing

Return back to our splicing data, and join it to another dataframe with new Attribute2, but new dataframe has information only for 4 Events

What to do??? > left and right joins

new_splicing_data <- mutate(tidy_splicing_data, PSI_value = as.numeric(PSI_value))

new_splicing_data
##   Event_ID PSI_value Group Peak
## 1 ENSG1_AB       0.1     A   NA
## 2 ENSG2_CD       0.2     B    5
## 3 ENSG3_EF       0.3     B   NA
## 4 ENSG4_GH       0.4     A    9
## 5 ENSG5_IJ       1.0     A   NA
splicing_data_count = data.frame(
  Event_ID = c('ENSG1_AB', 'ENSG2_CD', 'ENSG3_EF', 'ENSG4_GH'),
  count = c(43, 54, 72, 26))
splicing_data_count
##   Event_ID count
## 1 ENSG1_AB    43
## 2 ENSG2_CD    54
## 3 ENSG3_EF    72
## 4 ENSG4_GH    26

dplyr::left_join

dplyr::left_join(new_splicing_data, splicing_data_count, by="Event_ID")
##   Event_ID PSI_value Group Peak count
## 1 ENSG1_AB       0.1     A   NA    43
## 2 ENSG2_CD       0.2     B    5    54
## 3 ENSG3_EF       0.3     B   NA    72
## 4 ENSG4_GH       0.4     A    9    26
## 5 ENSG5_IJ       1.0     A   NA    NA

dplyr::right_join

dplyr::right_join(new_splicing_data, splicing_data_count, by="Event_ID")
##   Event_ID PSI_value Group Peak count
## 1 ENSG1_AB       0.1     A   NA    43
## 2 ENSG2_CD       0.2     B    5    54
## 3 ENSG3_EF       0.3     B   NA    72
## 4 ENSG4_GH       0.4     A    9    26

## 3 ENSG3_EF
## 4 ENSG4_GH
## 5 ENSG5_IJ

dplyr::mutate()

# Transform data in dataframe
new_splicing_data %>% mutate(new_PSI_value = 10*PSI_value)
##   Event_ID PSI_value Group Peak new_PSI_value
## 1 ENSG1_AB       0.1     A   NA             1
## 2 ENSG2_CD       0.2     B    5             2
## 3 ENSG3_EF       0.3     B   NA             3
## 4 ENSG4_GH       0.4     A    9             4
## 5 ENSG5_IJ       1.0     A   NA            10

dplyr::filter()

new_splicing_data %>% filter(PSI_value > 0.2)
##   Event_ID PSI_value Group Peak
## 1 ENSG3_EF       0.3     B   NA
## 2 ENSG4_GH       0.4     A    9
## 3 ENSG5_IJ       1.0     A   NA

dplyr::group_by() & dplyr::summarise()

new_splicing_data %>% 
  group_by(Group) %>%
  summarise(
    mean_value = mean(PSI_value)
  )
## # A tibble: 2  2
##   Group mean_value
##   <chr>      <dbl>
## 1 A           0.5 
## 2 B           0.25
